EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Broker
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced by Service Broker.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Forwarded Message Sent
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when Service Broker forwards a message.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Activation
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a queue monitor starts an activation stored procedure, sends a QUEUE_ACTIVATION notification, or when an activation stored procedure started by a queue monitor exits.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Connection
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Reports the status of a transport connection managed by Service Broker.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Conversation
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Reports the progress of a Service Broker conversation.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Forwarded Message Dropped
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when Service Broker drops a message that was intended to be forwarded.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Conversation Group
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when Service Broker creates a new conversation group or drops an existing conversation group.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Message Undeliverable
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when Service Broker is unable to retain a received message that should have been delivered to a service in this instance. For messages that should have been forwarded, see Broker:Forwarded Message Dropped Event Class.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Corrupted Message
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when Service Broker receives a corrupted message.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Message Classify
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when Service Broker determines the routing for a message. A message is classified for either local, remote, or delayed delivery.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Mirrored Route State Changed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the state of an active mirrored route (i.e. a route containing a mirror address that is currently being used by at least one conversation that is transmitting messages) changes. This reflects the change of state of one of the connections used by the mirrored route. This event also contains the status of those connections (eg. connected as primary, connected as mirror, disconnected due to some transport problem).

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Queue Disabled
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates a poison message was detected because there were five transaction rollbacks in a row on a Service Broker queue. The event contains the database ID and Queue ID of the queue that contains the poison message.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Remote Message Acknowledgement
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when an Acknowledgement has been received.

EVENT.NAME: Broker:Transmission
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that errors have occurred in the Service Broker Transport layer. The error number and state values indicate the source of the error.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: CLR
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced by execution of .Net Common Language Runtime (CLR) objects inside SQL Server.

EVENT.NAME: Assembly Load
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a request to load an assembly is executed. This can be useful when troubleshooting a query that uses CLR, when troubleshooting a slow running server that is running CLR queries, or when monitoring a server to gather user, database, success, or other information about assembly loads.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Cursors
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced by cursor operations.

EVENT.NAME: CursorPrepare
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the Microsoft SQL Server Database Engine compiles a SELECT statement associated with a cursor into an execution plan but does not create the cursor.

EVENT.NAME: CursorClose
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the Microsoft SQL Server Database Engine closes and deallocates a cursor.

EVENT.NAME: CursorExecute
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when Microsoft SQL Server Database Engine creates and populates a cursor from the execution plan created by a cursor prepare event.

EVENT.NAME: CursorImplicitConversion
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the Microsoft SQL Server Database Engine executes a Transact-SQL statement that is not supported by server cursors of the type requested. SQL Server database engine returns an error that indicates the cursor type has changed.

EVENT.NAME: CursorOpen
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when a cursor has been opened on an Transact-SQL statement.

EVENT.NAME: CursorUnprepare
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the Microsoft SQL Server Database Engine discards an execution plan.

EVENT.NAME: CursorRecompile
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the Microsoft SQL Server Database Engine recompiles a Transact-SQL cursor due to a schema change.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Database
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced when data or log files grow or shrink automatically.

EVENT.NAME: Data File Auto Grow
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that the data file grew automatically. This event does not get triggered if the data file is grown explicitly through ALTER DATABASE.

EVENT.NAME: Data File Auto Shrink
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that the data file has been shrunk.

EVENT.NAME: Log File Auto Shrink
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that the log file has been shrunk.

EVENT.NAME: Database Mirroring Connection
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates whether a connected state has changed between the principal, mirror, or witness in a database mirroring partnership.

EVENT.NAME: Database Mirroring State Change
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when the state of a mirrored database changes.

EVENT.NAME: Log File Auto Grow
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that the log file grows automatically. This event does not get triggered if the log file is grown explicitly through ALTER DATABASE.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Deprecation
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes deprecation related events.

EVENT.NAME: Deprecation Announcement
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when you use a feature that will be removed from future version of SQL Server, but will not be removed from the next major release of SQL Server. For greatest longevity of your applications, you should avoid using features that cause the Deprecation Announcement event class or the Deprecation Final Support event class.

EVENT.NAME: Deprecation Final Support
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when you use a feature that will be removed from the next major release of SQL Server. For greatest longevity of your applications, avoid using features that cause the Deprecation Announcement event class or the Deprecation Final Support event class.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Errors and Warnings
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced when a SQL Server error or warning is returned; for example, an error during the compilation of a stored procedure or an exception in SQL Server.

EVENT.NAME: Attention
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Collects all attention events, such as client interrupt request or when a client connection is broken.

EVENT.NAME: Missing Join Predicate
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a predicate joining two tables is not present. This can potentially result in long-running queries or inaccurate results. This event is only produced if both sides of the join return more than one row.

EVENT.NAME: Exception
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that an exception has occurred in SQL Server.

EVENT.NAME: Blocked process report
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a task has been blocked for more than a specified amount of time. This event class does not include system tasks or tasks which are waiting on non deadlock-detectable resources. To configure the frequency of reporting, use the sp_configure command to configure the blocked process threshold option.

EVENT.NAME: Background Job Error
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a background job has terminated abnormally. This condition may require the attention of a system administrator.

EVENT.NAME: Bitmap Warning
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that bitmap filtering has been disabled in a query.

EVENT.NAME: ErrorLog
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates error events logged in the SQL Server error log.

EVENT.NAME: CPU threshold exceeded
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when the resource governor detects a query has exceeded the CPU threshold value (REQUEST_MAX_CPU_TIME_SEC).

EVENT.NAME: EventLog
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates events logged in the Windows application event log.

EVENT.NAME: Database Suspect Data Page
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when a page is added to the suspect_pages table in msdb.

EVENT.NAME: Exchange Spill Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: The Exchange Spill event class indicates that communication buffers in a parallel query plan have been temporarily written to the tempdb database. This occurs rarely and only when a query plan has multiple range scans.

EVENT.NAME: Execution Warnings
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates any warnings that occurred during the execution of a SQL Server statement or stored procedure.

EVENT.NAME: Hash Warning
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a hash recursion, or cessation of hashing (hash bail) has occurred during a hashing operation.

EVENT.NAME: Missing Column Statistics
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that column statistics which would have been useful to the query optimizer are not present. This can cause the optimizer to choose a less efficient query plan than otherwise expected. You will not see this event produced unless the option to auto-create statistics is turned off.

EVENT.NAME: Sort Warnings
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates sort operations that do not fit into memory. Does not include sort operations involving the creation of indexes, only sort operations within a query (such as an ORDER BY clause used in a SELECT statement).

EVENT.NAME: User Error Message
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Displays the error message as seen by the user in the case or an error or exception. The error message text appears in the TextData field.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Full text
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced when full-text searches are started, interrupted, or stopped.

EVENT.NAME: FT:Crawl Aborted
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that an exception has been encountered during a full-text crawl. The error will usually cause the full-text crawl to stop. Check the Windows event log or the crawl log for more detailed error information.

EVENT.NAME: FT:Crawl Started
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a full-text crawl (population) has started. Use this event class to check if a crawl request is actually being picked up by worker tasks.

EVENT.NAME: FT:Crawl Stopped
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a full-text crawl (population) has stopped. The stop could due to a successfully completed crawl or a fatal error.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Locks
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced when a lock is acquired, cancelled, released, or has some other action performed on it.

EVENT.NAME: Lock:Escalation
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: A finer-grained lock has been converted to a coarser-grained lock.

EVENT.NAME: Deadlock graph
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs simultaneously with the Lock:Deadlock event class. The Deadlock Graph event class provides an XML description of the deadlock.

EVENT.NAME: Lock:Acquired
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that acquisition of a lock on a resource, such as a data page, has been achieved.\r\nThe Lock:Acquired and Lock:Released event classes can be used to monitor when objects are being locked, the type of locks taken, and for how long the locks were retained. Locks retained for long periods of time may cause contention issues and should be investigated.

EVENT.NAME: Lock:Cancel
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that the acquisition of a lock on a resource has been canceled (for example, due to a deadlock).

EVENT.NAME: Lock:Deadlock
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that two concurrent transactions have deadlocked each other by trying to obtain incompatible locks on resources that the other transaction owns.

EVENT.NAME: Lock:Timeout
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a request for a lock on a resource, such as a page, has timed out due to another transaction holding a blocking lock on the required resource.

EVENT.NAME: Lock:Deadlock Chain
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Is produced for each of the events leading up to the deadlock.

EVENT.NAME: Lock:Released
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a lock on a resource, such as a data page, has been released.\r\nThe Lock:Acquired and Lock:Released event classes can be used to monitor when objects are being locked, the type of locks taken, and for how long the locks were retained. Locks retained for long periods of time may cause contention issues and should be investigated.

EVENT.NAME: Lock:Timeout (timeout > 0)
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a request for a lock on a resource, such as a page, has timed out due to another transaction holding a blocking lock on the required resource. This event class behaves the same as the Lock:Timeout event class, except it does not include any events where the timeout value is 0.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: OLEDB
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced by OLE DB calls.

EVENT.NAME: OLEDB Call Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Displays OLE DB provider calls made by SQL Server for distributed queries and remote stored procedures.

EVENT.NAME: OLEDB DataRead Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Displays OLE DB IRowset::GetData calls made by SQL Server for fetching row data for distributed queries and remote stored procedures.

EVENT.NAME: OLEDB Errors
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that an OLE DB error has occurred.

EVENT.NAME: OLEDB Provider Information
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a distributed query is run and collects information corresponding to the provider connection. This event class contains all the properties collected from the remote provider using various property sets such as DBPROPSET_DATASOURCEINFO, SQLPROPSET_OPTHINTS, DBPROPSET_SQLSERVERDATASOURCEINFO (SQL Server only), DBPROPSET_SQLSERVERDBINIT (SQL Server only) and DBPROPSET_ROWSET and interface IDBInfo.

EVENT.NAME: OLEDB QueryInterface Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Displays OLE DB IUnknown::QueryInterface calls made by SQL Server for distributed queries and remote stored procedures.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Objects
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced when database objects are created, dropped, or altered.

EVENT.NAME: Object:Altered
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates an object has been altered (for example, by ALTER INDEX, ALTER TABLE, or ALTER DATABASE statements). Each DDL operation fires 2 complete events: 1 for "Begin" phase and another for either "Commit" or "Rollback" phase.

EVENT.NAME: Object:Created
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when an object has been created, such as for CREATE INDEX, CREATE TABLE, and CREATE DATABASE statements.

EVENT.NAME: Object:Deleted
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when an object has been deleted, such as in DROP INDEX and DROP TABLE statements.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Performance
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced when SQL data manipulation (DML) operators execute.

EVENT.NAME: Auto Stats
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Collects the events associated with the automatic creation and updating of statistics.

EVENT.NAME: Showplan XML
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when SQL Server executes a SQL Statement. Include the Showplan XML event class to identify the Showplan operators. The event class stores each event as a well defined XML document.

EVENT.NAME: Showplan Statistics Profile
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Displays the query-plan with full run-time details (including actual number of rows passing through each operation) of the SQL statement, which was executed. When the Showplan Statistics Profile event class is included in a trace, the BinaryData data column must be selected. If it is not, information for this event class will not be displayed in the trace.

EVENT.NAME: Plan Guide Unsuccessful
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that SQL Server could not produce an execution plan for a query or batch that contained a plan guide. SQL Server attempted to generate an execution plan for this query or batch without applying the plan guide. An invalid plan guide may be the cause of this problem. You can validate the plan guide by using the sys.fn_validate_plan_guide system function.

EVENT.NAME: Degree of Parallelism
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Describes the degree of parallelism assigned to the SQL statement.

EVENT.NAME: Performance statistics
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a compiled plan has been cached for the first time, recompiled, or evicted from the plan cache.

EVENT.NAME: Showplan All
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Displays the query-plan with full compile-time details (including costing estimates and column lists) of the SQL statement being executed. When the Showplan All event class is included in a trace, the BinaryData data column must be selected. If it is not, information for this event class will not be displayed in the trace.

EVENT.NAME: Showplan All For Query Compile
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when SQL Server compiles a SQL Statement. Include the Showplan All for Query Compile event class to identify the Showplan operators on SQL Server 2000 or SQL Server 7.0. This event class will also work on SQL Server 2005 or later, however the information included is a subset of the information available in Showplan XML For Query Compile.

EVENT.NAME: Plan Guide Successful
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that SQL Server successfully produced an execution plan for a query or batch that contained a plan guide.

EVENT.NAME: Showplan Text
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Displays the query-plan tree of the SQL statement being executed. Include the Showplan Text event class to identify the Showplan operators on SQL Server 2000 or SQL Server 7.0. This event class will also work on SQL Server 2005 or later, however the information included is a subset of the information available in Showplan All, Showplan XML Statistics Profile or Showplan XML.

EVENT.NAME: Showplan Text (Unencoded)
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Displays the plan tree of the SQL statement being executed. The Showplan Text (Unencoded) event class is the same as the Showplan Text event class, except the event information is formatted as text rather than as binary data.

EVENT.NAME: Showplan XML For Query Compile
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when SQL Server compiles a SQL Statement. Include the Showplan XML For Query Compile event class to identify the Showplan operators on SQL Server.

EVENT.NAME: Showplan XML Statistics Profile
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when SQL Server executes a SQL Statement. Include the Showplan XML Statististics Profile event class to identify the Showplan operators on SQL Server.

EVENT.NAME: SQL:FullTextQuery
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Displays performance information about individual Full-Text queries, including the query itself, the number of rows returned, and the duration of the query.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Progress Report
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes the Progress Report: Online Index Operation event class.

EVENT.NAME: Progress Report: Online Index Operation
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates the progress of an online index build operation. In most situations, the online index build process is a long running operation. This event class can be used to view the progress of an online index build while it is running.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Query Notifications
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes produced by query notifications processing.

EVENT.NAME: QN: Dynamics
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Tracks internal activities of query notifications.

EVENT.NAME: QN: Parameter table
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Allows to track creation and deletion of internal parameter tables. Those tables are used to store information about active subscriptions.

EVENT.NAME: QN: Subscription
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Identifies activities related to ongoing subscription registration and subscription firing.

EVENT.NAME: QN: Template
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Allows to track when a new subscription request falls into an already existing class of (Match) or a new class (Create). The third event subclass (Drop) stands for cleanup of templates for query classes without active subscriptions.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Scans
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are produced when tables and indexes are scanned.

EVENT.NAME: Scan:Started
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when a table or index scan has started.

EVENT.NAME: Scan:Stopped
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when a table or index scan has stopped.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Security Audit
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes that are used to audit server activity.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Add DB User Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records addition and removal of database users (Windows or SQL Server).

EVENT.NAME: Audit Server Operation Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when Audit operations in server, such as alter setting, resources, external access, or authorization are used.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Add Login to Server Role Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records addition or removal of logins to a fixed server role for sp_addsrvrolemember and sp_dropsrvrolemember.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Object GDR Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a GDR event for database objects such as assemblies and schemas, occurs.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Add Member to DB Role Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records addition and removal of members to a database role (fixed or user-defined) for sp_addrolemember, and sp_droprolemember.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Broker Conversation
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records both successful and unsuccessful Conversations.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Add Role Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records add or drop actions on database roles for sp_addrole and sp_droprole.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Server Alter Trace Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs for all statements that check for the ALTER TRACE permission. Statements that check for ALTER TRACE include those used to create or configure a trace, or to set a filter on trace.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Broker Login
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records both successful and unsuccessful adjacent Broker logins.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Addlogin Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records add and drop actions on SQL Server logins for sp_addlogin and sp_droplogin.

EVENT.NAME: Audit App Role Change Password Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records changes on the password of an application.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Server Object Management Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs in the case of CREATE, ALTER or DROP for server objects.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Backup/Restore Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records BACKUP and RESTORE events.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Change Audit Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records AUDIT modifications.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Change Database Owner
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the permissions to change the owner of a database is checked. This happens when the ALTER AUTHORIZATION statement is used to change the owner of a database.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Management Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a database is created, altered, or dropped.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Mirroring Login
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Reports audit messages related to database mirroring transport security.

EVENT.NAME: Audit DBCC Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records DBCC commands issued.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Object Access Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when database objects, such as schemas, are accessed.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Object Management Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a CREATE, ALTER or DROP statement is executed on database objects, such as schemas.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Object Take Ownership Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the owner is changedfor objects in database scope, such as assembly.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Schema Object Access Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records use of object permissions, successfully or unsuccessfully.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Operation Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when various operations in a database, such as checkpoint or subscribe query notification, occur.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Principal Impersonation Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when an impersonation occurs within the database scope, such as execute as user or setuser.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Principal Management Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when principals, such as users, are created, altered, or dropped from a database.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Database Scope GDR Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records GRANT, DENY, REVOKE statement permission events.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Login Change Password Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records SQL Server login password changes. Passwords are not recorded.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Server Object GDR Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a GDR event for a schema object, such as table or function, occurs.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Fulltext
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Tracks connections between the SQL Server process and the Full-Text filter daemon process.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Login
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Collects all new connection events since the trace was started, such as when a client requests a connection to a server running an instance of SQL Server.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Login Change Property Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records modifications on login property, except passwords, for sp_defaultdb and sp_default language.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Server Scope GDR Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs in the case of a GDR event for permissions in server scope, such as create login.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Login Failed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a login attempt to SQL Server from a client failed.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Login GDR Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records grant, revoke, and deny actions on Windows account login rights for sp_grantlogin, sp_revokelogin, and sp_denylogin.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Logout
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Collects all new disconnect events since the trace was started, such as when a client issues a disconnect command.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Object Derived Permission Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records when a CREATE, ALTER, or DROP command is issued for the specified object.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Schema Object GDR Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records GRANT, DENY, REVOKE object permission events.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Schema Object Management Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a CREATE, ALTER or DROP statement is executed on schema objects, such as tables or views.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Schema Object Take Ownership Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the permissions to change the owner of schema object (such as a table, procedure, or function) is checked. This happens when the ALTER AUTHORIZATION statement is used to assign an owner to an object.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Server Object Take Ownership Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the owner is changed for objects in server scope.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Server Principal Impersonation Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when there is an impersonation in server scope, such as execute as login.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Statement Permission Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records use of statement permissions.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Server Principal Management Event
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs in the case of create, alter or drop for server principals.

EVENT.NAME: Audit Server Starts And Stops
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Records service shut down, start, and pause activities.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Server
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes general server events.

EVENT.NAME: Mount Tape
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a tape mount request is received. Use this event class any time you want to monitor tape mount requests and their success or failure.

EVENT.NAME: Server Memory Change
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when SQL Server memory usage increases or decreases by 1 megabyte or 5% of the maximum server memory, whichever is greater.

EVENT.NAME: Trace File Close
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a trace file has been closed during rollback.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Sessions
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes server session event classes.

EVENT.NAME: ExistingConnection
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates properties of existing user connections when trace was started. Server fires one ExistingConnection event per user connection.

EVENT.NAME: PreConnect:Completed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when a LOGON trigger or resource governor classifier function completes execution.

EVENT.NAME: PreConnect:Starting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when a LOGON trigger or resource governor classifier function starts execution.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Stored Procedures
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes produced by the execution of stored procedures.

EVENT.NAME: SP:CacheRemove
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when an item is removed from the procedure cache.

EVENT.NAME: RPC Output Parameter
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Information about output parameters of previously executed remote procedure call.

EVENT.NAME: RPC:Completed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a remote procedure call has been completed.

EVENT.NAME: SP:CacheMiss
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when a stored procedure is not found in the procedure cache.

EVENT.NAME: RPC:Starting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a remote procedure call has started.

EVENT.NAME: SP:CacheInsert
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when an item is inserted into the procedure cache.

EVENT.NAME: SP:Completed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when the stored procedure has completed.

EVENT.NAME: SP:CacheHit
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when a procedure is found in the cache.

EVENT.NAME: SP:Recompile
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that the stored procedure is recompiling.

EVENT.NAME: SP:Starting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when the stored procedure has started.

EVENT.NAME: SP:StmtCompleted
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a Transact-SQL statement within a stored procedure has completed.

EVENT.NAME: SP:StmtStarting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a Transact-SQL statement within a stored procedure has started.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: TSQL
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes produced by the execution of Transact-SQL statements passed to an instance of SQL Server from the client.

EVENT.NAME: SQL:StmtStarting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the Transact-SQL statement is starting.

EVENT.NAME: Exec Prepared SQL
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when a prepared Transact-SQL statement or statements have been executed by SqlClient, ODBC, OLE DB or DB-Library.

EVENT.NAME: Prepare SQL
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates when an SQL statement or statements have been prepared for use by ODBC, OLE DB or DB-Library.

EVENT.NAME: SQL:BatchCompleted
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the Transact-SQL statement has completed.

EVENT.NAME: SQL:BatchStarting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a Transact-SQL batch is starting.

EVENT.NAME: SQL:StmtCompleted
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when the Transact-SQL statement has completed.

EVENT.NAME: Unprepare SQL
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that the SqlClient, ODBC, OLE DB, or DB-Library has unprepared (deleted) a prepared Transact-SQL statement or statements.

EVENT.NAME: SQL:StmtRecompile
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when a statement in a batch (including stored procedures) recompiles. This event should be used starting in SQL Server 2005 instead of SP:Recompile to trace statement-level recompilations.

EVENT.NAME: XQuery Static Type
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Occurs when SQL Server executes an XQuery. This event class provides the static type of the XQuery expression. In case of the value() method, the statically inferred type is displayed after the implied atomization of the expression.

EVENTCATEGORY.NAME: Transactions
EVENTCATEGORY.DESCRIPTION: Includes event classes produced by the execution of Microsoft Distributed Transaction Coordinator transactions or by writing to the transaction log.

EVENT.NAME: DTCTransaction
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Tracks MS DTC coordinated transactions between two or more databases.

EVENTCOLUMSUBCLASS.NAME: TM failed while in prepared state

EVENT.NAME: SQLTransaction
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Tracks BEGIN TRANSACTION, COMMIT TRANSACTION, SAVE TRANSACTION, and ROLLBACK TRANSACTION statements.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Commit Tran completed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a COMMIT TRANSACTION request completed. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

EVENT.NAME: TransactionLog
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Tracks when transaction are written to the transaction log.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Begin Tran completed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a BEGIN TRANSACTION request has been completed. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Begin Tran starting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a BEGIN TRANSACTION request is starting. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Commit Tran starting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a COMMIT TRANSACTION request is starting. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Promote Tran completed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a PROMOTE TRANSACTION request has completed. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Promote Tran starting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a PROMOTE TRANSACTION request is starting. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Rollback Tran completed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a ROLLBACK TRANSACTION request completed. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Rollback Tran starting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a ROLLBACK TRANSACTION request is starting. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Save Tran completed
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a SAVE TRANSACTION request has completed. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

EVENT.NAME: TM: Save Tran starting
EVENT.DESCRIPTION: Indicates that a SAVE TRANSACTION request is starting. The request was sent from the client through Transaction Management interface.

COLUMN.NAME: TextData
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Text value dependent on the event class captured in the trace.

COLUMN.NAME: BinaryData
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Binary value dependent on the event class captured in the trace.

COLUMN.NAME: DatabaseID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: ID of the database specified by the USE database statement, or the default database if no USE database statement has been issued for a given connection.

COLUMN.NAME: TransactionID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: System-assigned ID of the transaction.

COLUMN.NAME: LineNumber
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Displays the number of the line containing the error.

COLUMN.NAME: NTUserName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Windows user name.

COLUMN.NAME: NTDomainName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Windows domain to which the user belongs.

COLUMN.NAME: HostName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of the computer on which the client is running. This data column is populated if the host name is provided by the client. To determine the host name, use the HOST_NAME function.

COLUMN.NAME: ClientProcessID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The process ID of the application calling SQL Server.

COLUMN.NAME: ApplicationName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of the client application that created the connection to SQL Server. This column is populated with the values passed by the application rather than the displayed name of the program.

COLUMN.NAME: LoginName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of the login of the user (either SQL Server security login or the Windows login credentials in the form of DOMAIN\Username).

COLUMN.NAME: SPID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Server Process ID assigned by SQL Server to the process associated with the client.

COLUMN.NAME: Duration
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Amount of time taken by the event. Although the server measures duration in microseconds, SQL Server Profiler can display the value in milliseconds, depending on the setting in the Tools>Options dialog.

COLUMN.NAME: StartTime
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Time at which the event started, when available.

COLUMN.NAME: EndTime
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Time at which the event ended. This column is not populated for starting event classes, such as SQL:BatchStarting or SP:Starting.

COLUMN.NAME: Reads
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Number of logical disk reads performed by the server on behalf of the event.

COLUMN.NAME: Writes
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Number of physical disk writes performed by the server on behalf of the event.

COLUMN.NAME: CPU
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Amount of CPU time (in milliseconds) used by the event.

COLUMN.NAME: Permissions
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Integer value representing the type of permissions checked.

COLUMN.NAME: Severity
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Severity level of an exception.

COLUMN.NAME: EventSubClass
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Type of event subclass. This data column is not populated for all event classes.

COLUMN.NAME: ObjectID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: System-assigned ID of the object.

COLUMN.NAME: Success
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: 1 = success. 0 = failure (for example, a 1 means success of a permissions check and a 0 means a failure of that check).

COLUMN.NAME: IndexID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: ID for the index on the object affected by the event. To determine the index ID for an object, use the indid column of the sysindexes system table.

COLUMN.NAME: IntegerData
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Integer value dependent on the event class captured in the trace.

COLUMN.NAME: ServerName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of the SQL Server traced.

COLUMN.NAME: EventClass
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Event class name.

COLUMN.NAME: ObjectType
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Value representing the type of the object involved in the event. This value corresponds to the type column in sysobjects.

COLUMN.NAME: NestLevel
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Integer representing the data returned by @@NESTLEVEL.

COLUMN.NAME: State
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Equivalent to an error state code.

COLUMN.NAME: Error
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Error number of a given event. Often this is the error number stored in sysmessages.

COLUMN.NAME: Mode
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Integer used by various events to describe a state the event has received or is requesting.

COLUMN.NAME: Handle
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Integer used by ODBC, OLE DB, or DB-Library to coordinate execution with the server.

COLUMN.NAME: ObjectName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The name of the object being referenced.

COLUMN.NAME: DatabaseName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of the database in which the statement of the user is running.

COLUMN.NAME: FileName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The logical name of the file being modified.

COLUMN.NAME: OwnerName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Database user name of the object owner.

COLUMN.NAME: RoleName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of an application role being enabled.

COLUMN.NAME: TargetUserName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: For actions which target a database user (for instance, granting permission to a user), the name of that user.

COLUMN.NAME: DBUserName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: SQL Server user name of the client.

COLUMN.NAME: LoginSid
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Security identification number (SID) of the logged-in user. You can find this information in the syslogins table of the master database. Each SID is unique for each login in the server.

COLUMN.NAME: TargetLoginName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: For actions which target a login (for instance, adding a new login), the name of the targeted login.

COLUMN.NAME: TargetLoginSid
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: For actions which target a login (for instance, adding a new login), the security identification number (SID) of the targeted login.

COLUMN.NAME: ColumnPermissions
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Indicator of whether a column permission was set. Parse the statement text to determine exactly which permissions were applied to which columns.

COLUMN.NAME: LinkedServerName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of the linked server.

COLUMN.NAME: ProviderName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of the OLE DB provider.

COLUMN.NAME: MethodName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of the OLE DB method.

COLUMN.NAME: RowCounts
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The number of rows in the batch.

COLUMN.NAME: RequestID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The ID of the request containing the statement.

COLUMN.NAME: XactSequence
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: A token to describe the current transaction.

COLUMN.NAME: EventSequence
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The sequence of a given event within the request.

COLUMN.NAME: BigintData1
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Bigint value dependent on the event class captured in the trace.

COLUMN.NAME: BigintData2
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Bigint value dependent on the event class captured in the trace.

COLUMN.NAME: GUID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: GUID value dependent on the event class captured in the trace.

COLUMN.NAME: IntegerData2
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Integer value dependent on the event class captured in the trace.

COLUMN.NAME: ObjectID2
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The ID of the related object or entity if available.

COLUMN.NAME: Type
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Integer value dependent on the event class captured in the trace.

COLUMN.NAME: OwnerID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Type of the object owning a lock (for lock events)

COLUMN.NAME: ParentName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The name of the schema the object is within.

COLUMN.NAME: IsSystem
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Indicates whether the event occurred on a system process or a user process. 1 = system, 0 = user.

COLUMN.NAME: Offset
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The starting offset of the statement within the stored procedure or batch.

COLUMN.NAME: SourceDatabaseID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: ID of the Database in which the source of the object exists.

COLUMN.NAME: SqlHandle
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: 64 bit hash based on the text of an adhoc query or the database and object ID of a sql object. This value can be passed to sys.dm_exec_sql_text() to retrieve the associated text or object.

COLUMN.NAME: SessionLoginName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The login name of the user who originated the session. For example, if you connect to SQL Server using Login1 and execute a statement as Login2, LoginSessionName will show Login1; while LoginName will show Login2. This column will display both SQL Server and Windows logins.

COLUMN.NAME: PlanHandle
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Indicates the GUID for the plan handle. This GUID can be used by sys.dm_exec_query_plan function for retrieving the execution plan XML.

COLUMN.NAME: GroupID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Indicates the GroupID classified by the resource governor for the current session.

COLUMN.NAME: ReplaySequence
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The sequence of replayable event generated in DReplay preprocess.

COLUMN.NAME: ThinkTime
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Amount of time taken from the last event completion in same session.

COLUMN.NAME: EndSequence
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The sequence of completed event.

COLUMN.NAME: AttentionTimeout
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Amount of time of attention.

COLUMN.NAME: ConnectionID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Connection ID assigned in preprocessing.

COLUMN.NAME: ReplaySPID
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Server Process ID assigned by SQL Server to the process associated with replay client.

COLUMN.NAME: ReplayHostName
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Name of the computer on which the client is running during replay.

COLUMN.NAME: SubmitTime
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Time at which the event submitted.

COLUMN.NAME: ExecutionAndFetchTime
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Time taken for query execution including result fetching

COLUMN.NAME: ExecutionTime
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: Time taken for query execution excluding result fetching

COLUMN.NAME: SourceRow
COLUMN.DESCRIPTION: The original row number for the event executed
